      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 2,
      "creation_date" : 1491931112,
      "post_id" : 10292186,
      "comment_id" : 73767828,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "currentTimeMillis should not be used for calculating elapsed time as it&#39;s not monotonic (you might end up with negative elapsed time!). See e.g <a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/2978598/will-system-currenttimemillis-always-return-a-value-previous-calls\" title=\"will system currenttimemillis always return a value previous calls\">stackoverflow.com/questions/2978598/&hellip;</a>"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1430276,
      "reputation" : 31,
      "user_id" : 1352827,
      "user_type" : "unregistered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1fa4d9947e5e493e9434a78e1ed0f858?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "sarvesh",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1352827/sarvesh"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1474404491,
    "last_edit_date" : 1474404491,
    "creation_date" : 1335245365,
    "answer_id" : 10292186,
    "question_id" : 3382954,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Nanotime is in fact not even good for elapsed time because it drifts away signficantly more than currentTimeMillis.  Furthermore nanotime tends to provide excessive precision at the expense of accuracy.  It is therefore highly inconsistent,and needs refinement.</p>\n\n<p>For any time measuring process,currentTimeMillis (though almost as bad), does better in terms of balancing accuracy and precision.  </p>\n"
